# Laravel to React (Standalone SPA) Conversion Guide

## Overview

This guide covers migrating a Laravel application (Blade/Livewire/Inertia) into a **decoupled architecture**: Laravel becomes a pure **JSON API backend** (using Sanctum for auth), and React becomes a standalone **Single Page Application** managed independently. Unlike the Inertia approach, there is no server-side HTML rendering for pages — React runs fully client-side.

## Tech Stack

- **Laravel**: 12.x (API only)
- **React**: 19.x
- **Vite**: 6.x (standalone React build, separate from Laravel)
- **React Router**: v7.x (client-side routing)
- **Axios** or native `fetch` for API calls
- **Laravel Sanctum**: API token authentication
- **Tailwind CSS**: 4.x (in React app via PostCSS)

---

## Architecture Overview

```
BEFORE (Monolith)                  AFTER (Decoupled SPA)
──────────────────────────         ─────────────────────────────────
Browser → Laravel Routes           Browser → React SPA (static files / CDN)
         → Blade/Livewire                   → React Router (client routes)
         → PHP renders HTML                 → fetch/Axios → Laravel JSON API
                                            → Laravel validates + returns JSON
```

### Key Mental Shifts

| Laravel Monolith | Laravel API + React SPA |
|------------------|------------------------|
| Routes render HTML pages | Routes return JSON only |
| Session auth (cookies) | Sanctum token auth (Bearer) |
| `Redirect::route()` | API returns JSON; React Router navigates |
| Blade `{{ $var }}` | JSX `{variable}` |
| Livewire public properties | React `useState` |
| `@foreach` / `@if` | `.map()` / ternary / `&&` |
| Laravel validation → redirect back | 422 JSON with `errors` object |
| Flash messages | API JSON `{ message: '...' }` / toast library |
| Laravel Mix / Vite (monolith) | Standalone Vite React app |

